# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The Intuition of traditional approach has been talked about in too many posts, will not be repeated here.
- The only optimization in Example, say:
    - array a1 has length of 101
    - array a2 has length of 10
    - So, total length is 111
    - Median is 56th smallest element
    - half of it is 28
    - Because, a2.length < 28, traditional approach will just throw away 28 elements from a1
    - instead we could
        - calculate 56-10=46 and then
        - compare 10th element in a2 vs 46th element in a1, we either
        - get rid of 10 from a2, then next round we get answer from a1, or
        - get rid of 46 from a1, that's more than 28, thus the improvement
            - The improvement is not significant enough to change the TC/SC, this is just for fun.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: (m+n)log(m+n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```java
class Solution {
    public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] a1, int[] a2) {
        int m = a1.length, n = a2.length, len = m + n;
        int k = len / 2;
        int x = find(a1, a2, 0, 0, k+1);
        if (len % 2 == 1) return (double) x;

        return ((double) x + find(a1, a2, 0, 0, k)) / 2;
    }

    private int find(int[] a1, int[] a2, int i, int j, int k) { // i: idx for a1, j: idx for a2
        if (i == a1.length) return a2[j+k-1]; // corner case 1
        if (j == a2.length) return a1[i+k-1]; // corner case 2
        if (k == 1) return Math.min(a1[i], a2[j]); // corner case 3

        int d1 = k / 2, d2 = k - d1; // delta 1 vs delta 2
        if (i+d1 > a1.length) { // if a1 side is out of bound, we can get rid of more from a2 side
            d1 = a1.length-i;
            d2 = k - d1;
        } else if (j + d2 > a2.length) { // if a2 side is out of bound, we can get rid of more from a1 side
            d2 = a2.length - j;
            d1 = k - d2;
        }

        int i2 = i + d1 -1, j2 = j + d2 - 1;

        return a1[i2] > a2[j2] ? find(a1, a2, i, j2+1, d1) : find(a1, a2, i2+1, j, d2);
    }
}
```

