# Intuition
The intuition behind this approach is that if we can partition the arrays in such a way that the number of elements on the left equals the number of elements on the right, then the median will be the average of the maximum element on the left and the minimum element on the right. We can use binary search to find the correct partition indices in logarithmic time complexity, and then compute the median in constant time.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
Calculate the total length of the merged array, which is m + n.
Determine the middle index of the merged array, which is (m + n) / 2.
Traverse through both arrays at the same time using two pointers, i and j, initialized to 0.
Compare the values at the current indices of both arrays.
If nums1[i] is less than or equal to nums2[j], add nums1[i] to the merged array and increment i.
If nums1[i] is greater than nums2[j], add nums2[j] to the merged array and increment j.
Repeat steps 4-6 until either i reaches m or j reaches n.
If i has reached m, add the remaining elements of nums2 to the merged array.
If j has reached n, add the remaining elements of nums1 to the merged array.
If the length of the merged array is even, return the average of the values at the middle index and the index before it.
If the length of the merged array is odd, return the value at the middle index.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(log(m+n))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

