# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- Given two sorted arrays, we need to find the median of their merged array.
- We can find the median of a sorted array in O(1) time. Therefore, the problem reduces to merging the two arrays and finding the median of the merged array.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- We can use a two-pointer approach to merge the two arrays into a new array in sorted order.
- We initialize two pointers, one for each array, and compare the elements at their respective pointers.
- The smaller element is added to the new array and its corresponding pointer is incremented.
- This process continues until we have exhausted one of the arrays.
- If there are still elements remaining in the other array, we add them to the new array.
- Finally, we compute the median of the new array based on its length.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(m+n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(m+n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {
        int i=0,i1=0,i2=0;
        int l=nums1.length+nums2.length;
        int[] a =new int[(l/2)+1];
        while(i<a.length){
               if(i1<nums1.length&&i2<nums2.length){
                   a[i++] = nums1[i1]<nums2[i2] ? nums1[i1++]:nums2[i2++];
               }
               else if(i1<nums1.length){
                   a[i++]=nums1[i1++];
               }
               else{
                   a[i++]=nums2[i2++];
               }
        } 
        if(l%2==1){
            return a[a.length-1];
        }
        else{double t=(a[a.length-2]+a[a.length-1]);
        return t/2.00;
        }
    }
}
```

