solutions.content:
### Algorithm Overview
 Use a binary search to find the smallest component of the median.
 Note: the smallest component is either in `a` or `b`. If the
 binary search returns `Ok(...)` then the smallest component is in `a`,
 `Err(...)` indicates it's in `b`.

 Then if the total number of elements is odd, the smallest component is only the component
 and is hence the median. This case corresponds to the first two cases of the match statement. 

 When the total number of elements is even, the median is the average of the smallest component
 and the next larger element. This case corresponds to the last two cases of the match statement.

 Note: The binary search considers a candidate partition of `a`,`x`, as `(a[0..=x],a[x+1..])`. If
 `a[x]` is the smallest component of the median then we know how many elements of from `b`
 must be <= and >= to `a[x]` in `b`. The partition of `b`, `y = s-x` corresponds to these elements.
 All elements in `b[0..s-x]` are `<= b[s-x-1]`, similarly  All elements in `b[s-x..]` are `<= b[s-x]`.
 Either: 
 - `a[x] < b[s-x-1] <=  b[s-x]`:  `a[x]` is too small, hence `x` too small.
 - `b[s-x-1] <= b[s-x] < a[x]`:  `a[x]` is too large, hence `x` too large.
 - `b[s-x-1] <= a[x] <= b[s-x]`:  `a[x]` is the smallest median component. 

When the binary search fails, `b[s-x]` ends being the smallest median component symmetrically,
and `a[x]` is the smallest value larger then `b[s-x]` in `a`.


### Asymptotic Complexity Analysis
`O(1)` before and after the `binary_search`,
The `binary_search` starts with a range of the shortest array length.
Each step of the binary search is `O(1)`, hence overall: `O(log(min(m,n)))`

### Code

```rust
pub fn find_median_sorted_arrays(mut a: Vec<i32>, mut b: Vec<i32>) -> f64 {
    if a.len() > b.len() {std::mem::swap(&mut a, &mut b);}
    let s = (a.len() + b.len() - 1)/2;

    let partition = binary_search(0..a.len(), |x| {
        if b[s-x] < a[x] {Ordering::Greater}
        else if s-x > 0 && b[s-x-1] > a[x] {Ordering::Less}
        else {Ordering::Equal}
    });

    match (partition, (a.len() + b.len())&0b1 == 1) {
        (Ok(x) , true) => a[x]   as f64,
        (Err(x), true) => b[s-x] as f64,
        (Ok(x) , false) => (a[x]   + unwrap_min(a.get(x+1), b.get(s-x))) as f64/2.0,
        (Err(x), false) => (b[s-x] + unwrap_min(a.get(x), b.get(s-x+1))) as f64/2.0,
    }
}

use std::ops::Range;
use std::cmp::Ordering;
fn unwrap_min(a:Option<&i32>, b:Option<&i32>) -> i32 {
    match (a,b) {
        (Some(&a), Some(&b)) => a.min(b),
        (Some(x),None)|(None,Some(x)) => *x,
        (None,None) => panic!()
    }
}

fn binary_search(Range{mut start, mut end}: Range<usize>, fnx: impl Fn(usize) -> Ordering) -> Result<usize,usize> {
    while end > start {
        let next = (start+end)/2;
        match fnx(next) {
            Ordering::Less => start = next+1,
            Ordering::Greater => end = next,
            Ordering::Equal => return Ok(next)
        }
    }
    return Err(end)
}

